Abstract
Genome-wide association studies of physical activity traits have mapped numerous loci, yet the molecular mechanisms through which exercise influences human biology remain poorly defined. Mechanistic progress has been limited by heritability-dominated signals, siloed single-omic analyses, and the lack of integrative models that connect genetic associations to causal, system-level pathways. We introduce the first deep learning, multi-omic framework for exercise genomics, unifying causal inference, molecular topology, protein structure, and functional context within a supervised Graph Neural Network (GNN) with experimental validation. Using linkage disequilibrium-aware Mendelian randomisation with accelerometer-derived vigorous physical activity as the exposure, we integrated four omic layersâ€”plasma proteomics, blood CpG methylation, blood single-cell transcriptomics, and plasma glycomics. The GNN prioritised a coherent, multi-omic network of exercise-responsive genes spanning glycosylation (glycosyltransferases, glycoproteins), immune signalling (IgG modules, cytokine clusters), proteostasis and autophagy (hydrolases), redox regulation (oxidoreductases), and stress-response regulators (transcription factors, kinases). Pathway annotation and alignment with ageing biology using differentially methylated regions and principal-component features from five biological ageing clocks (Horvath, Hannum, DunedinPACE, PhenoAge, Proteomic Clock) revealed a convergent architecture linking autophagy, oxidative stress, DNA damage and repair, hormonal regulation, and neuroendocrine signalling. Finally, we validated model predictions in humans, demonstrating acute exercise-induced shifts in plasma glycomic markers consistent with GNN-predicted glycomic remodelling. This work establishes the first deep learning, multi-omic map of exercise-responsive pathways in humans and identifies actionable regulators that couple habitual physical activity to immunometabolic resilience and healthy ageing trajectories.
Keywords: deep learning, graph neural network, mendelian randomisation, multi-omics, physical activity, accelerometry, ageing, ageing clocks
